URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS648045591	2018-10-29 09:15:00	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			X					Ecuador	EC	Esmeraldas	EC-E							Alto Tambo, northwest	L7817599	P	1.0280000	-78.5940000	1990-07-27		obsr268012	S47819369	Historical	P62	EBIRD				1	0		0	1	0		The end of the road was ca. 20 road km northwest of Alto Tambo (ca. 325 m). Our camp site was located ca. 45 minute walk from the end of the road to the south bank of the Rio San Jose. The camp was in virtually untouched primary forest and we eventually had trails on the other side of the river that allowed access to primary, foothill forest. See field notes (deposited at Univ. of Kansas Biodiversity Institute) for more details and hand drawn map of the area. Most bird species had finished breeding (apparently late March-early May) as most were in the final stages of the molt cycle. Very little was vocalizing, even at dawn. The following list is a compilation of species recorded, 4-28 July 1990. See daily lists for specifics. Does not include birds recorded that I did not see or hear. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS551111381	2020-08-23 08:08:28	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			X					Ecuador	EC	Esmeraldas	EC-E							Playa de Oro Reserva de Los Tigrillos	L615475	H	0.8484740	-78.7822723	2008-11-24		obsr179592	S40586476	Historical	P62	EBIRD				2	0		0	1	0		It rained overnight and into the morning. After 05:30 breakfast Julio and Jorge the boatmen took us across the river to the Peñon del Santo Trail, which starts just opposite the lodge. For the first hour or so it was wet and we didn’t see much. As arranged the guys picked us up at 1pm and we headed back to the lodge for lunch, finding a lonely Laughing Gull perched on a gravel bar as we crossed the river. Late afternoon we took a short spin on the Pueblo Trail (downstream behind the lodge).

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS899101830	2020-04-21 09:46:36	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			X					Ecuador	EC	Esmeraldas	EC-E							Playa de Oro Reserva de Los Tigrillos	L615475	H	0.8484740	-78.7822723	2019-04-28	15:00:00	obsr637980	S67540417	Historical	P62	EBIRD	150			2	1		0	1	0		Left Selva Alegre the main gateway to the lowland forest of Playa de Oro and headed up San Tiago River at around 13:00. En-route we made a couple of stops for supplies. At around 14:30 it started to rain and so the last part of the journey was spent getting soaked with no coat and no umbrella to hand. We arrived at the rustic lodge set within the forest at 15:00 and after settling into the basic rooms had a quick bite to eat. The lodge was a former mining settlement in the middle of the forest which has been converted to an eco-lodge and so is ideally placed to access the fast disappearing lowland forests of the Choco region. We headed out onto the trails behind the lodge but the rain was very heavy and the light levels in the forest low. The trails were sodden and we saw very little.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS187950073	2021-08-10 10:45:54.49769	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			2					Ecuador	EC	Pichincha	EC-P							Rio Silanche--general area	L1641819	H	0.1171009	-79.1360923	2003-08-08	06:15:00	obsr103185	S13561079	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	625	10.000		7	1		0	1	0		SIMÓN BOLÍVAR ROAD. Today we birded a road about 7-10 km west of the town of Pedro Vicente Maldonado. The dirt road took off to the north and we birded in and out about 6-10 km. It's a road known for birds of the Chocó lowlands. There were many hearts of palm groves and African oil palm groves interspersed with areas of lowland tropical and foothill forests and cutover areas. According to Willey this area is rapidly being converted into palm groves and losing more and more forest each year. It still has some very good western lowland birding though for Chocó species and we found the birding to be quite good. In fact, this was our biggest day of the trip in terms of number of species seen. All our birding was along this road from 6:15a-4:40p. It was quite warm and humid. Priscilla wasn't feeling well again today so she stayed back at Séptimo Paraíso and Breanna stayed with her.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS794643961	2019-09-16 17:57:37	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			2					Ecuador	EC	Pichincha	EC-P							La Delicia--Guayabillas road (lower part below Mashpi turnoff)	L2244167	H	0.1957150	-78.8721150	2019-08-13	11:32:00	obsr528710	S58976962	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	292	5.000		2	1	G4515531	0	1	0				
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS935070060	2020-05-31 09:22:02	1945	species	Dusky Pigeon	Patagioenas goodsoni			1					Ecuador	EC	Pichincha	EC-P							Mashpi--Lodge and trails	L2244142	H	0.1661250	-78.8788780	2019-08-16		obsr637980	S69874997	Historical	P62	EBIRD					1		0	1	0		This is an amalgamated list for our stay at the lodge from 14:15 on 15th August to 12:30 on 17th August.----Day 1 - 15th August PM--We arrived at Mashpi Lodge at 14:15 and were immediately swept into a world of cloud forest dudes and impeccable hospitality. After dropping our bags we were summoned to the first of a series of programmed walks with our knowledgeable guide, Anderson. We walked a trail near the lodge to a waterfall seeing very few birds, the only birds of note that I saw were a pair of Moss-backed Tanager and Dusky Antbird. After the trail we went to the sky-bikes, basically these are giant tandems suspended on a wire which you peddle through the canopy. This was a great way to see the forest canopy as we were suspended on our bikes at some 70m above the forest floor. Finally, we climbed the observation tower where we obtained great views across the forest canopy as the sun fell. Birds here were Crimson-rumped Toucanet, Swallow-tanager, Rufous-throated Tanager and Moss-backed Tanager.----Day 2 - 16th August--We awoke to the sounds of the rainforest in our beautiful room at Mashpi Lodge, as the light increased a few birds were seen. Just before breakfast I spent a short while birding from the veranda of the lodge. After breakfast we then walked down the Magnolia Trail and then along the river to the Dragonfly. The Dragonfly is basically a cablecar that extends for several kilometres through and above the canopy of the forest. At its maximum height above the ground this cablecar is elevated some 200m and its fairly hair-raising. From a birding perspective the highlight was a stunning male Black-tipped Cotinga at close range, unfortunately I had the wrong lens on my camera and by the time I had switched lenses the bird had gone. After a leisurely lunch we took a short drive then a 200m walk to the Life Centre, here, we watched from the viewpoint across the forest and waited to see what came into the banana feeders as well as spending some time in the butterfly house where we were shown a number of species and handled a range of caterpillars.  After a quick freshen up we did a short night walk from the lodge where the only birds were a calling Black-and-white Owl and a perched Common Pauraque. ----Day 3 - 17th August--It rained most of the night and we awoke to light rain and dense fog. After a leisurely breakfast we took a bus up to the Hummingbird Garden near to the lodge entrance gate. Here there was a good range of hummingbird species including Green Thorntail, Rufous-tailed Hummingbird, Empress Brilliant, Velvet-purple Coronet, Violet-tailed Sylph, Crowned Woodnymph, White-whiskered Hermit, Brown Inca and Andean Emerald. Other species included White-throated Quail-dove, Glistening-green Tanager, Golden-naped Tanager, Flame-faced Tanager, Moss-backed Tanager and Golden-collared Honeycreeper.We headed back to the lodge for 10:30, packed our bags, checked out of the room and had lunch we were collected from the lodge at 12:30 and we began the journey bag to Quito.
